---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
const description = 'About Grass Whisperer: practical, independent lawn-care information for UK home gardeners who want to understand what their lawn is doing.';
---
<BaseLayout title="About" {description}>
  <header class="simple-hero"><div class="container"><span class="eyebrow">About Grass Whisperer</span><h1>Useful lawn advice, without the salesman’s grin.</h1><p>Most lawns do not need a grand rescue plan. They need someone to notice what changed, make one sensible job of it, and leave the grass time to respond.</p></div></header>
  <section><div class="container about-grid"><aside>Practical help for ordinary British gardens, including the awkward corners.</aside><div><h2>How the site looks at a lawn</h2><p>Start with what is actually in front of you: thin grass by the gate, puddles that keep coming back, a patch that turns blue-grey in dry weather, or a mower that has taken too much off. Then work backwards to the likely cause.</p><p>Some jobs are worth doing straight away. Some are better left until the soil warms, the rain arrives or the lawn has had a chance to recover. The guides are written for the UK, but your soil, shade, rainfall and local restrictions still get the final say.</p><h2>What you will not find here</h2><p>No miracle cure for every brown patch. No fertiliser recommendation just because it is spring. And no pretending that a drainage failure or subsidence problem is something a bag of seed can sort out.</p><p class="disclaimer"><strong>Worth saying:</strong> This is general gardening information, not site-specific professional advice. Get a qualified person involved if you suspect subsidence, failed drainage, buried utilities, chemical contamination or serious plant disease. Product labels and local water-use rules always take priority.</p></div></div></section>
</BaseLayout>
